# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt was born in Haverstraw, New York.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] His mother, Ann Gurnee, was of French Huguenot descent, while his father, John Hewitt, was from Staffordshire in England and had emigrated to the U.S. in 1796 to work on a steam engine to power a water plant in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt attended Columbia College on a scholarship.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] After graduating from the college in 1842, he taught mathematics there, and became a lawyer several years later.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] From 1843 to 1844, Hewitt traveled to Europe with his student, Edward Cooper, the son of industrialist entrepreneur Peter Cooper, and another future New York City mayor.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] During their return voyage, the pair were shipwrecked together.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] After this, Hewitt became "virtually a member of the Cooper family", and in 1855 married Edward's sister, Sarah Amelia.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] In 1845, financed by Peter Cooper, Hewitt and Edward Cooper started an iron mill in Trenton, New Jersey, the Trenton Iron Company, where, in 1854, they produced the first structural wrought iron beams, as well as developing other innovative products.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt's younger brother, Charles, was a manager at the iron mill.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt also invested in other companies, in many case serving on their boards.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt supervised the construction of the Cooper Union, Peter Cooper's free educational institution, and chaired its board of trustees until 1903.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Tilden, Cooper prominently campaigned to remove the corrupt "Tweed Ring", led by William M.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] "Boss" Tweed, from control of Tammany Hall, and to reorganize the Democratic Party in New York, which Tweed controlled for years through his political machine.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt first ventured into electoral politics in 1874, when he won a seat in the U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] House of Representatives, where he initially served two terms representing New York's 10th congressional district, from March 4, 1875, to March 3, 1879.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] During his first stint in Congress, he was made head of the Democratic National Committee in 1876, when Tilden ran unsuccessfully for President.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] After defeating James O'Brien, his successor in Congress who was a staunch opponent of Tammany Hall, for the Democratic nomination in the 10th district during the 1880 elections, Hewitt regained his old seat and once again served in the U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] House from 4 March 1881 to 30 December 1886.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt's most famous speech was made at the opening of the Brooklyn Bridge between Manhattan and Brooklyn in 1883.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt was elected mayor of New York City in 1886.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He defeated the labor candidate Henry George as well as the Republican candidate Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt's election campaign had the support of Tammany Hall.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] The endorsement was formal and included organizational muscle.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt refused to review the Saint Patrick's Day parade, a decision that alienated much of the Democratic Party's Irish–American base in the city.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt also refused to allow Tammany the control of patronage they wanted, and Croker saw to it that Hewitt was not nominated for a second term.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt was considered a defender of sound financial management.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He is quoted as saying "Unnecessary taxation is unjust taxation".
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt also upheld the civil service reform in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He oversaw the passage of the Rapid Transit Act of 1894, which would provide public funding for the construction of the first New York City Subway line.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] A 1993 survey of historians, political scientists and urban experts conducted by Melvin G.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Holli of the University of Illinois at Chicago ranked Hewitt as the twenty-sixth-best American big-city mayor to have served between the years 1820 and 1993.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt had many investments in natural resources, including considerable holdings in West Virginia, where William Nelson Page (1854–1932) was one of his managers.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He was also an associate of Henry Huttleston Rogers (1840–1909), a financier and industrialist who was a key man in the Standard Oil Trust, and a major developer of natural resources.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] One of Hewitt's investments handled by Rogers and Page was the Loup Creek Estate in Fayette County, West Virginia.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] The Deepwater Railway was a subsidiary initially formed by the Loup Creek investors to ship bituminous coal from coal mines on their land a short distance to the main line of the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway (C&O) along the Kanawha River.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] After rate disputes, the short line railroad was eventually expanded to extend all the way into Virginia and across that state to a new coal pier at Sewell's Point on Hampton Roads.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] In 1890 Hewitt partnered with Edward Cooper and Hamilton McKown Twombly in forming the American Sulphur Company, which then entered into a 50/50 agreement with Herman Frasch and his partners to form the Union Sulphur Company.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] As philanthropist Hewitt was interested in education.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Columbia University gave him the degree of LL.D. in 1887, and he was the president of its alumni association in 1883, and a trustee from 1901 until his death.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] In 1876, he was elected president of the American Institute of Mining Engineers, and was a founder and trustee of the Carnegie Institution of Science.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He was also a trustee of Barnard College and of the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Abram Hewitt died at his New York City home on January 18, 1903, and was interred at Green-Wood Cemetery.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt's daughters, Amy, Eleanor, and Sarah Hewitt, built a decorative arts collection that was for years exhibited at the Cooper Union and later became the core collection of the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] His son, Peter Cooper Hewitt (1861–1921), was a successful inventor, while another son, Edward Ringwood Hewitt (1865–1957), was also an inventor, a chemist and an early expert on fly-fishing.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He published *Telling on the Trout*, among other books.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] Hewitt's youngest son, Erskine Hewitt (1871–1938), was also a lawyer and philanthropist in New York City.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] He donated Ringwood Manor to the State of New Jersey in 1936.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] On February 18, 1909, Erskine Hewitt was named a director of the newly formed National Reserve Bank of the City of New York.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/abram-stevens-hewitt] On March 2, 1909, Hewitt was elected chairman.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Born in Lakeville, Connecticut in 1832, Holley graduated from Brown University in 1853.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] He worked at Corlias & Nightingale (Corliss Steam Engine Works) as a workman and student.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] He also served as a locomotive engineer on Stonington and Providence Railroad, and then entered the New York Locomotive Works as a draughtsman.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] During his early 20s, Holley was a close friend of Zerah Colburn, the well-known locomotive engineer and journalist/publisher who founded *Railway Advocate* and later the journal to Holley.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] In 1857, the two visited Britain and France to study the rail system and compiled a report for the presidents of American railroads, *The Permanent Way* published in 1858.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Around the same time, Holley wrote to The New York Times accurately predicting screw propulsion would supersede side wheels for ocean navigation.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Holley was also a construction consultant for development of Stevens Battery.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] In 1860, the two traveled together on the maiden voyage of Isambard Kingdom Brunel's *Great Eastern*.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Holley's most famous book, *A treatise on ordnance and armor* published in 1865, followed a visit he made to Britain in 1863 when he again met Zerah Colburn.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Holley was a creative inventor, who received 15 patents in the US.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Ten of those fifteen were for improvements in the Bessemer process, for which he purchased the US rights in 1863 on behalf of a consortium of investors.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] He soon designed and built Bessemer plants in Troy, New York, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, and Braddock, Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] He planned or was consulted on a dozen others.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] Holley served as president of the American Institute of Mining Engineers, and vice-president of the American Society of Civil Engineers.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] In 1880 Holley chaired the first meeting of the founders of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) in the offices of the *American Machinist* on 16 February and afterwards served as vice-president of the society.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] He was also a trustee for Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and lecturer at School of Mines, Columbia College.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] In 1882 he was awarded the Bessemer Gold Medal of the British Iron and Steel Institute for his services to the industry.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] The Holley medal is given out by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in his honor.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/alexander-lyman-holley] He received many honors, including being made an honorary member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1892; and in 1890 a monument was unveiled in Washington Square Park, New York bearing a bust of him.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The **American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical, and Petroleum Engineers** (**AIME**) is a professional association for mining and metallurgy, with over 145,000 members.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The association was founded in 1871 by 22 mining engineers in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania, and was one of the first national engineering societies in the country.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] It is the parent organization of four Member Societies, the Society for Mining, Metallurgy, and Exploration (SME), The Minerals, Metals & Materials Society (TMS), the Association for Iron and Steel Technology (AIST), and the Society of Petroleum Engineers (SPE).
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The organization is currently based in San Ramon, California.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] Founded as the **American Institute of Mining Engineers** (AIME), the institute had a membership at the beginning of 1915 of over 5,000, made up of honorary, elected, and associate members.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The annual meeting of the institute was held in February, with other meetings during the year as authorized by the council.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The institute published three volumes of *Transactions* annually and a monthly *Bulletin* which appeared on the first of each month.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The headquarters of the institute was in the Engineering Societies' Building in New York City.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] Following creation of the Petroleum Division in 1922, the Iron and Steel Division in 1928 and the Institute of Metals Division in 1933 the name of the society was changed in 1957 to the American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical and Petroleum Engineers.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] Three of the current member societies were then created from the divisions, increasing to four in 1974 when the Iron and Steel Society (ISS) was formed.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] In 2004 ISS merged with the Association of Iron and Steel Engineers (AISE) to form the Association for Iron and Steel Technology (AIST) whilst remaining a member society of AIME.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The society presents around 25 awards each year at its annual conference.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] Member societies also disburse their own awards, including the Percy Nicholls Award, awarded by SME jointly with American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The following individuals have held the position of President of this organization.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers] The Society for Mining, Metallurgy & Exploration publishes the monthly magazine *Mining Engineering* since 1949.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/association-for-iron-and-steel-technology] These divisions are served by a number of committees that organize sessions at the AISTech conference and oversee training and education activities relating to these areas of knowledge.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/association-for-iron-and-steel-technology] Two sub-committees exist, namely „Digitalization“ and „Decarbonization“, which act as interconnecting committees as they demand a liaison in each committee to coordinate efforts in their respective field of expertise.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] He received his A.B. in mathematics from Columbia University (1919), B.S. in engineering from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (1921), and D.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] Ing. and Sc.D. from the University of Nancy, France (1922, 1933).
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] His employment started in 1919 at the General Electric Laboratories in Pittsfield, Massachusetts.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] He joined Union Carbide Research Laboratories in 1926 as a research metallurgist, where he subsequently served as chief metallurgist starting in 1931, vice-president (1945), and president (1948).
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] He subsequently served as director of research for the Union Carbide Corporation (starting 1954), and vice-president of research (1955).
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] In later years he was president and chief executive officer the Salk Institute for Biological Studies.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] During World War II he held key advisory posts for ordnance, and led the metals branch of the Technical Industrial Intelligence Committee in Europe.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] After the war, he served on the Defense Science Board and the Naval Research Advisory Committee, and as consultant to the Los Alamos, Oak Ridge, Argonne, and Brookhaven National Laboratories, and the Knolls Atomic Power Laboratory.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] Kinzel was active in professional organizations, notably as the president of the American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical, and Petroleum Engineers (1958) and chairman of the Division of Engineering and Industrial Research of the National Research Council (1960).
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] He was a founding member of the National Academy of Engineering, and a member of the National Academy of Sciences, the American Philosophical Society, and the MIT Corporation.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] He was a trustee of the California Institute of Technology, the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, and a member of the board of System Development Corporation, Beckman Instrument Company, etc.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/augustus-braun-kinzel] He was also the recipient of many distinguished service awards such as the illustrious IRI Medal from the Industrial Research Institute.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/benjamin-bowditch-thayer] He was born on October 20, 1862, in San Francisco, California.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/benjamin-bowditch-thayer] He attended the public schools in Quincy, Massachusetts then the Harvard School of Engineering and Applied Sciences at Harvard University.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/benjamin-bowditch-thayer] He served on the Naval Consulting Board in 1915.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/benjamin-bowditch-thayer] He died on February 22, 1933, at New York Hospital following an operation.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] The **Canadian Institute of Mining, Metallurgy and Petroleum** (CIM) is a not-for-profit technical society of professionals in the Canadian minerals, metals, materials and energy industries.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] CIM's members are convened from industry, academia and government.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In March 1898, the Canadian Mining Institute was founded in Montreal at the second annual meeting of the Federated Canadian Mining Institute, which was dissolved.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] The Institute was incorporated by an Act of Parliament to include all former provincial groups except The Mining Society of Nova Scotia, which remained a separate body.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 1902, The Institute formed its first Branches in Sherbrooke, Quebec, Kingston, Ontario, and Nelson, British Columbia.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 1918, the Mining Society of Nova Scotia formally became affiliated with the Canadian Mining Institute.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 1920, Metallurgy was added to the name to recognize the inclusion of this discipline.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 1942, the Institute made CIM its official abbreviation.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 1990, "Canadian Institute of Mining, Metallurgy and Petroleum" became the official name of the Institute by an Act of Parliament.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 1996, CIM published its Guidelines for the Estimation, Classification and Reporting of Resources and Reserves.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] This document became an integral part of National Instrument 43-101 (NI 43-101), the set of rules for reporting and displaying information from mineral properties owned by companies listed on Canadian exchanges that came into effect on Feb.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] A book entitled "Pride and Vision" by E.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] Tina Crossfield was published in commemoration of the event.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 2018, CIM celebrated its 120th anniversary.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] It also launched a completely redesigned site for all of its Standards, Best Practices & Guidance for Mineral Resources & Mineral Reserves materials, including the 2014 update of CIM Definition Standards.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] In 2023, CIM celebrated its 125th anniversary.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] CIM Branches are organized geographically within three Districts (Western, Central and Eastern) across Canada to address the local needs of members.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] They discuss regional issues concerning the industry and undertake CIM’s mission at a local level.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] CIM’s 11 technical societies strive to promote the development of the many facets of Canada’s minerals, metals, materials and petroleum industries.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] Technically driven, they come together to discuss issues of concern in their specific field pertaining to the discovery, production and utilization of resources.
[src:american-institute-of-mining-metallurgical-and-petroleum-engineers/canadian-mining-institute] The institute bestows several awards annually to individuals for their outstanding achievements and contributions to their respective fields and to the mining and minerals industries in general.
